points.description:
**Default methods** are methods defined in an interface with the `default` keyword that provide a concrete implementation. They allow interfaces to evolve without breaking existing implementations: 
```java
public interface MyInterface {
    void abstractMethod(); // Regular abstract method

    default void defaultMethod() {
        System.out.println("Default implementation");
    }
}
```

When a class implements multiple interfaces with the same default method, the **diamond problem** arises. Java resolves this by requiring the implementing class to override the conflicting method: 
```java
public interface A { default void method() { /* impl A */ } }
public interface B { default void method() { /* impl B */ } }

public class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public void method() {
        A.super.method(); // Choose implementation from A
        // Or B.super.method(); // Or from B
        // Or custom implementation
    }
}
```

Default methods enable new design patterns, such as the **Trait pattern**, where interfaces with default methods act like **traits** (reusable chunks of behavior) that can be mixed into classes without inheritance: 
```java
public interface Loggable {
    default Logger getLogger() {
        return LoggerFactory.getLogger(getClass());
    }

    default void logInfo(String message) {
        getLogger().info(message);
    }
}

// Any class can now become loggable
public class MyService implements Loggable {
    public void process() {
        logInfo("Processing started"); // Uses the trait method
        // ...
    }
}
```

Since Java 9, interfaces can also have **private methods** (both instance and static), which enable code reuse within the interface itself: 
```java
public interface Validator {
    default boolean validateWithLogging(String input) {
        log("Validating: " + input);
        return validate(input);
    }

    default boolean validate(String input) {
        return !isNullOrEmpty(input);
    }

    private boolean isNullOrEmpty(String text) { // Helper method
        return text == null || text.isEmpty();
    }

    private static void log(String message) { // Private static helper
        System.out.println(message);
    }
}
```

A **functional interface** is an interface that has exactly one abstract method (SAM - Single Abstract Method). It can be annotated with `@FunctionalInterface`, though this is optional: 
```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Runnable {
    void run();
}
```

Functional interfaces enable **lambda expressions**, which provide a concise way to represent an anonymous function that can be passed around: 
```java
// Traditional anonymous class
Runnable runnable1 = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
};

// Lambda expression
Runnable runnable2 = () -> System.out.println("Hello");
```

**Method references** provide a shorthand syntax for lambda expressions that call a single existing method: 
```java
// Lambda expression
Function<String, Integer> strLength = s -> s.length();

// Method reference equivalent
Function<String, Integer> strLength = String::length;
```
There are four types of method references:
1. Reference to a static method: `ClassName::staticMethod`
2. Reference to an instance method of a particular object: `object::instanceMethod`
3. Reference to an instance method of an arbitrary object of a particular type: `ClassName::instanceMethod`
4. Reference to a constructor: `ClassName::new`

Many functional interfaces provide default methods for combining functions: 
```java
// Combining Predicates
Predicate<String> isNotEmpty = s -> !s.isEmpty();
Predicate<String> isNotTooLong = s -> s.length() <= 10;
Predicate<String> isValid = isNotEmpty.and(isNotTooLong);

// Chaining Functions
Function<String, String> trim = String::trim;
Function<String, String> toUpperCase = String::toUpperCase;
Function<String, String> trimAndUpperCase = trim.andThen(toUpperCase);
```

The Java compiler can often infer the types in lambda expressions from the context, making code more concise: 
```java
// Explicit parameter types
Comparator<String> comp = (String s1, String s2) -> s1.length() - s2.length();

// Inferred parameter types
Comparator<String> comp = (s1, s2) -> s1.length() - s2.length();
```

While the standard library covers many common cases, you can create custom functional interfaces for specific needs: 
```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface TriFunction<T, U, V, R> {
    R apply(T t, U u, V v);

    default <S> TriFunction<T, U, V, S> andThen(Function<? super R, ? extends S> after) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(after);
        return (T t, U u, V v) -> after.apply(apply(t, u, v));
    }
}
```

Lambda expressions can access variables from their enclosing scope if they are final or effectively final (not modified after initialization): 
```java
String prefix = "User: ";

// Works because prefix is effectively final
Function<String, String> addPrefix = name -> prefix + name;

// Would cause compilation error if you tried to modify prefix after this:
// prefix = "Customer: ";
```

Lambda expressions can take various forms:
```java
// No parameters
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

// One parameter (parentheses optional)
Consumer<String> c = s -> System.out.println(s);

// Multiple parameters
BiFunction<Integer, Integer, Integer> add = (a, b) -> a + b;

// Multiple statements
Comparator<String> comp = (s1, s2) -> {
    int result = s1.length() - s2.length();
    return result != 0 ? result : s1.compareTo(s2);
};
```

Lambdas can capture variables from their enclosing scope (closure), but these variables must be effectively final (not modified after initialization):
```java
int threshold = 10;
// This works because threshold is effectively final
Predicate<Integer> isGreaterThanThreshold = n -> n > threshold;

// This would cause a compilation error:
// threshold = 20;
```

**Method references** provide a shorthand for lambdas that simply call a single method:
```java
// Lambda form
Function<String, Integer> strLength = s -> s.length();

// Method reference form
Function<String, Integer> strLength = String::length;
```

Four types of method references:
1. Static method: `ClassName::staticMethod`
2. Instance method of specific object: `object::instanceMethod`
3. Instance method of arbitrary object: `ClassName::instanceMethod`
4. Constructor: `ClassName::new`

Lambda expressions can be challenging with checked exceptions:
```java
// Won't compile - FileReader throws checked exceptions
// and Function doesn't declare them
// Function<String, BufferedReader> readerFn = 
//     s -> new BufferedReader(new FileReader(s));

// Options for handling checked exceptions in lambdas:

// 1. Use a try-catch inside the lambda
Function<String, BufferedReader> readerFn1 = s -> {
    try {
        return new BufferedReader(new FileReader(s));
    } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
        throw new RuntimeException(e);
    }
};

// 2. Create a wrapper that converts checked exceptions to unchecked
@FunctionalInterface
interface CheckedFunction<T, R> {
    R apply(T t) throws Exception;

    static <T, R> Function<T, R> unchecked(CheckedFunction<T, R> f) {
        return t -> {
            try {
                return f.apply(t);
            } catch (Exception e) {
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        };
    }
}

// Now we can write:
Function<String, BufferedReader> readerFn2 = 
    CheckedFunction.unchecked(s -> new BufferedReader(new FileReader(s)));
```

The basic syntax is `ContainingClass::methodName` or `object::methodName`. For example: 
```java
// Lambda expression
Consumer<String> printer = s -> System.out.println(s);

// Equivalent method reference
Consumer<String> printer = System.out::println;
```

The JVM automatically matches parameters between the functional interface method and the referenced method. This can sometimes be non-intuitive, especially with instance methods:

```java
// For a static method or constructor, parameters map directly:
BiFunction<Integer, Integer, Integer> min = Math::min;
// Equivalent to: (a, b) -> Math.min(a, b)

// For an instance method of an arbitrary object,
// the first parameter becomes the receiver of the method call:
BiFunction<String, String, Boolean> contains = String::contains;
// Equivalent to: (s1, s2) -> s1.contains(s2)
```

Method references work with varargs methods as well:

```java
// Method with varargs
static void printAll(String... messages) {
    for (String message : messages) {
        System.out.println(message);
    }
}

// Method reference to varargs method
Consumer<String[]> printer = YourClass::printAll;
```

When referencing overloaded methods, the compiler determines which overloaded method to use based on the functional interface's method signature:

```java
class Processor {
    static String process(String s) { return s.toUpperCase(); }
    static Integer process(Integer i) { return i * 2; }
}

// This works because the compiler knows which overload to use
// based on the Function<String, String> context
Function<String, String> stringProcessor = Processor::process;

// Similarly, this uses the Integer overload
Function<Integer, Integer> intProcessor = Processor::process;
```

Method references can refer to generic methods, with appropriate type inference:

```java
class Utilities {
    public static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list) {
        return list.isEmpty() ? null : list.get(0);
    }
}

// The compiler infers the appropriate type
Function<List<String>, String> firstGetter = Utilities::getFirst;
```

Streams can be created from various sources:
```java
// From collections
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("a", "b", "c");
Stream<String> fromList = list.stream();

// From arrays
String[] array = {"a", "b", "c"};
Stream<String> fromArray = Arrays.stream(array);

// From values
Stream<String> fromValues = Stream.of("a", "b", "c");

// Empty stream
Stream<String> empty = Stream.empty();
```

Streams can be processed in parallel for potential performance improvements on multi-core systems:
```java
// Convert a sequential stream to parallel
list.stream().parallel().forEach(System.out::println);

// Create a parallel stream directly
list.parallelStream().forEach(System.out::println);
```

Considerations for parallel streams:
1. Operations should be stateless and non-interfering
2. The data source should be efficiently splittable (like ArrayList, not LinkedList)
3. The operations should be computationally intensive to offset parallelization overhead
4. The order of processing is not guaranteed unless specifically ordered

The `Collectors` utility class provides sophisticated reduction operations:
```java
// Grouping by a property
Map<Department, List<Employee>> byDept = employees.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDepartment));

// Multi-level grouping
Map<Department, Map<EmployeeStatus, List<Employee>>> byDeptAndStatus = employees.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getStatus)));

// Partitioning (special case of grouping with boolean predicate)
Map<Boolean, List<Employee>> partitioned = employees.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(e -> e.getSalary() > 50000));

// Custom statistics
Map<Department, DoubleSummaryStatistics> salaryStatsByDept = employees.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.summarizingDouble(Employee::getSalary)));
```

There are several ways to create an Optional:
```java
// Empty Optional
Optional<String> empty = Optional.empty();

// Optional with non-null value
Optional<String> withValue = Optional.of("Hello"); // Throws NPE if argument is null

// Optional that may contain null
Optional<String> nullable = Optional.ofNullable(possiblyNullString); // Returns empty if argument is null
```

Common Operations with Optional:
```java
// Check if value is present
if (optional.isPresent()) {
    // Use the value
    String value = optional.get();
}

// Modern approach (avoiding get())
optional.ifPresent(value -> System.out.println(value));

// Get value or default
String result = optional.orElse("Default");

// Get value or compute default
String result = optional.orElseGet(() -> computeDefault());

// Get value or throw exception
String result = optional.orElseThrow(() -> new NoSuchElementException());
```

Optional provides methods to transform values:
```java
// Map value if present
Optional<Integer> length = optional.map(String::length);

// FlatMap for operations that return Optional
Optional<User> user = findUserById(id);
Optional<String> email = user.flatMap(User::getEmailOptional);

// Filter values
Optional<String> longName = optional.filter(s -> s.length() > 5);
```

Optional shines when chaining operations that might return null:
```java
// Without Optional (prone to NPE)
String streetName = null;
if (user != null) {
    Address address = user.getAddress();
    if (address != null) {
        Street street = address.getStreet();
        if (street != null) {
            streetName = street.getName();
        }
    }
}

// With Optional
String streetName = Optional.ofNullable(user)
                           .flatMap(User::getAddressOptional)
                           .flatMap(Address::getStreetOptional)
                           .map(Street::getName)
                           .orElse("Unknown");
```

Java 9 added more Optional methods:
```java
// If value present, return it; otherwise return other Optional
Optional<String> result = optional.or(() -> Optional.of("alternative"));

// Convert Optional to Stream (empty or singleton)
Stream<String> stream = optional.stream();

// If present, perform action; otherwise perform other action
optional.ifPresentOrElse(
    value -> System.out.println("Found: " + value),
    () -> System.out.println("Not found")
);
```

Optional enables several design patterns:

1. **Null Object Pattern** - Optional.empty() serves as a type-safe null object
2. **Builder Pattern Enhancement** - Builders can return Optional for properties that might not be set
3. **Functional Error Handling** - Using Optional with flatMap for composable error handling:

```java
public interface UserService {
    Optional<User> findById(String id);  // May not find user
}

public interface OrderService {
    Optional<Order> createOrder(User user, Product product);  // Order creation might fail
}

// Usage with functional composition
public Optional<Order> processOrder(String userId, String productId) {
    return userService.findById(userId)
        .flatMap(user -> productService.findById(productId)
            .flatMap(product -> orderService.createOrder(user, product)));
}
```

Creating objects with the new API:
```java
// Current date/time
LocalDate today = LocalDate.now();
LocalTime now = LocalTime.now();
LocalDateTime dateTime = LocalDateTime.now();
ZonedDateTime zonedDateTime = ZonedDateTime.now();
Instant timestamp = Instant.now();

// From specific values
LocalDate date = LocalDate.of(2023, Month.MAY, 15);
LocalTime time = LocalTime.of(14, 30, 0);
LocalDateTime dateTime = LocalDateTime.of(2023, Month.MAY, 15, 14, 30);
ZonedDateTime zonedDateTime = ZonedDateTime.of(dateTime, ZoneId.of("America/New_York"));
```

Performing basic operations:
```java
// Adding/subtracting time
LocalDate tomorrow = today.plusDays(1);
LocalDate lastMonth = today.minusMonths(1);

// Extracting components
int year = today.getYear();
Month month = today.getMonth();
int day = today.getDayOfMonth();
DayOfWeek dayOfWeek = today.getDayOfWeek();

// Comparing dates
boolean isBefore = date1.isBefore(date2);
boolean isAfter = date1.isAfter(date2);
boolean isEqual = date1.isEqual(date2);
```

Measuring time intervals:
- **Period**: Time-based amount of time (years, months, days)
- **Duration**: Time-based amount of time in seconds and nanoseconds

```java
// Creating periods/durations
Period period = Period.between(date1, date2);
Duration duration = Duration.between(time1, time2);

// Manual creation
Period period = Period.of(1, 2, 3); // 1 year, 2 months, 3 days
Duration duration = Duration.ofHours(2); // 2 hours

// Using periods/durations
LocalDate future = today.plus(period);
LocalTime later = now.plus(duration);
```

Converting between strings and date-time objects:
```java
// Using predefined formatters
LocalDate date = LocalDate.parse("2023-05-15");
LocalTime time = LocalTime.parse("14:30:00");

// Using custom formatters
DateTimeFormatter formatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("dd/MM/yyyy");
LocalDate date = LocalDate.parse("15/05/2023", formatter);
String formattedDate = date.format(formatter);

// Localized formatting
DateTimeFormatter italianFormatter = DateTimeFormatter
    .ofPattern("d MMMM yyyy")
    .withLocale(Locale.ITALIAN);
String formattedDate = date.format(italianFormatter); // 15 maggio 2023
```

Working with time zones and offsets:
```java
// Getting available zones
Set<String> zoneIds = ZoneId.getAvailableZoneIds();

// Converting between time zones
ZonedDateTime nyTime = ZonedDateTime.now(ZoneId.of("America/New_York"));
ZonedDateTime tokyoTime = nyTime.withZoneSameInstant(ZoneId.of("Asia/Tokyo"));

// Working with offsets
OffsetDateTime offsetDateTime = OffsetDateTime.now(ZoneOffset.UTC);
OffsetDateTime newYorkTime = offsetDateTime.withOffsetSameInstant(ZoneOffset.of("-04:00"));
```

Making complex date adjustments:
```java
// Built-in adjusters
LocalDate firstDayOfMonth = date.with(TemporalAdjusters.firstDayOfMonth());
LocalDate lastDayOfYear = date.with(TemporalAdjusters.lastDayOfYear());
LocalDate nextMonday = date.with(TemporalAdjusters.next(DayOfWeek.MONDAY));

// Custom adjuster
TemporalAdjuster nextPayday = temporal -> {
    LocalDate date = LocalDate.from(temporal);
    int day = date.getDayOfMonth();
    // Payday is on the 15th and last day of the month
    if (day < 15) {
        return date.withDayOfMonth(15);
    }
    return date.with(TemporalAdjusters.lastDayOfMonth());
};
LocalDate nextPay = date.with(nextPayday);
```

The API provides a **Clock** class for better testability:
```java
// Using system clock (default behavior)
LocalDate today = LocalDate.now();

// Using a specific clock
Clock clock = Clock.fixed(Instant.parse("2023-05-15T10:00:00Z"), ZoneId.of("UTC"));
LocalDate fixedDate = LocalDate.now(clock); // Always 2023-05-15

// This makes unit tests deterministic
```

Reading and writing text files:
```java
// Reading a text file line by line
try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("input.txt"))) {
    String line;
    while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
        System.out.println(line);
    }
}

// Writing to a text file
try (BufferedWriter writer = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output.txt"))) {
    writer.write("Hello, World!");
    writer.newLine();
    writer.write("Another line");
}
```

Streams are often chained together to add functionality:
```java
// Reading with buffering for efficiency
InputStream fileIn = new FileInputStream("data.bin");
BufferedInputStream bufferedIn = new BufferedInputStream(fileIn);

// Adding data processing
InputStream fileIn = new FileInputStream("data.zip");
BufferedInputStream bufferedIn = new BufferedInputStream(fileIn);
ZipInputStream zipIn = new ZipInputStream(bufferedIn);
```

Working with binary data:
```java
// Reading binary data
try (DataInputStream in = new DataInputStream(
        new BufferedInputStream(
            new FileInputStream("data.bin")))) {
    int intValue = in.readInt();
    double doubleValue = in.readDouble();
    boolean boolValue = in.readBoolean();
}

// Writing binary data
try (DataOutputStream out = new DataOutputStream(
        new BufferedOutputStream(
            new FileOutputStream("data.bin")))) {
    out.writeInt(42);
    out.writeDouble(3.14159);
    out.writeBoolean(true);
}
```

Handling different character encodings:
```java
// Specifying character encoding
try (Reader reader = new InputStreamReader(
        new FileInputStream("text.txt"), StandardCharsets.UTF_8)) {
    // Read UTF-8 encoded text
}

try (Writer writer = new OutputStreamWriter(
        new FileOutputStream("text.txt"), StandardCharsets.UTF_16)) {
    // Write text in UTF-16 encoding
}
```

Java NIO.2 (java.nio.file) provides more modern file operations:
```java
// Reading a file with Files utility class
List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(Paths.get("input.txt"), StandardCharsets.UTF_8);

// Writing lines to a file
Files.write(Paths.get("output.txt"), Arrays.asList("Line 1", "Line 2"), StandardCharsets.UTF_8);

// Reading/writing large files more efficiently with streams
try (Stream<String> stream = Files.lines(Paths.get("large.txt"))) {
    stream.filter(line -> line.contains("important"))
          .forEach(System.out::println);
}

// File copy with one line
Files.copy(Paths.get("source.txt"), Paths.get("destination.txt"), 
           StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);
```

Using memory mapped files for extremely large files:
```java
try (RandomAccessFile file = new RandomAccessFile("hugefile.data", "rw")) {
    FileChannel channel = file.getChannel();

    // Map part of the file into memory
    MappedByteBuffer buffer = channel.map(
        FileChannel.MapMode.READ_WRITE, 0, channel.size());

    // Work with the buffer like any other ByteBuffer
    while (buffer.hasRemaining()) {
        buffer.put((byte) (buffer.get() * 2)); // Double each byte value
    }
}
```

Key patterns and practices:

1. **Always use try-with-resources** to ensure streams are closed

2. **Decorator Pattern**: I/O streams implementation is a classic example of the Decorator pattern, allowing functionality to be layered dynamically

3. **Buffering**: Almost always wrap basic streams with buffered streams for performance

4. **Character vs. Byte**: Use character streams for text and byte streams for binary data

5. **NIO.2 for modern code**: Prefer java.nio.file over legacy I/O when possible for more concise, feature-rich code

6. **Scanner for parsing**: Use Scanner for parsing formatted text input:
```java
try (Scanner scanner = new Scanner(new File("data.txt"))) {
    scanner.useDelimiter(",");
    while (scanner.hasNext()) {
        String value = scanner.next();
        // Process value
    }
}
```

Exception handling patterns:
```java
// Basic try-catch-finally
try {
    // Code that might throw exceptions
    FileReader file = new FileReader("file.txt");
    // Process file...
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    // Handle the specific exception
    System.err.println("File not found: " + e.getMessage());
} catch (IOException e) {
    // Handle a broader exception
    System.err.println("IO error: " + e.getMessage());
} finally {
    // Always executed, regardless of exception
    // Close resources, clean up, etc.
}

// Try-with-resources (Java 7+)
try (FileReader reader = new FileReader("file.txt");
     BufferedReader buffered = new BufferedReader(reader)) {
    String line;
    while ((line = buffered.readLine()) != null) {
        System.out.println(line);
    }
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.err.println("Error reading file: " + e.getMessage());
}
// Resources automatically closed, even with exceptions
```

Throwing exceptions:
```java
// Declaring checked exceptions
public void readFile(String path) throws IOException {
    // Method code...
}

// Throwing an exception
public void validateAge(int age) {
    if (age < 0) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age cannot be negative");
    }
}

// Rethrowing exceptions
public void processFile(String path) throws IOException {
    try {
        // Code that might throw IOException
    } catch (IOException e) {
        // Log the exception
        logger.log("Error processing file", e);
        // Rethrow it
        throw e;
    }
}
```

Exception chaining preserves the original cause:
```java
public void processData() throws ServiceException {
    try {
        // Code that might throw various exceptions
        repository.fetchData();
    } catch (SQLException e) {
        // Wrap in an application-specific exception
        throw new ServiceException("Data processing failed", e);
    }
}

// Later, both exceptions are available
try {
    service.processData();
} catch (ServiceException e) {
    System.err.println("Service error: " + e.getMessage());
    Throwable cause = e.getCause();
    if (cause != null) {
        System.err.println("Caused by: " + cause.getMessage());
    }
}
```

Creating custom exceptions:
```java
// Checked custom exception
public class ResourceNotFoundException extends Exception {
    private String resourceId;

    public ResourceNotFoundException(String resourceId) {
        super("Resource not found: " + resourceId);
        this.resourceId = resourceId;
    }

    public ResourceNotFoundException(String resourceId, Throwable cause) {
        super("Resource not found: " + resourceId, cause);
        this.resourceId = resourceId;
    }

    public String getResourceId() {
        return resourceId;
    }
}

// Unchecked custom exception
public class BusinessRuleViolationException extends RuntimeException {
    private String rule;

    public BusinessRuleViolationException(String rule, String message) {
        super(message);
        this.rule = rule;
    }

    public String getRule() {
        return rule;
    }
}
```

Exception handling patterns and best practices:

1. **Exception Translation**: Convert lower-level exceptions to ones that make sense in your API
```java
try {
    // Low-level database code
} catch (SQLException e) {
    throw new DataAccessException("Failed to fetch user", e);
}
```

2. **Exception Enrichment**: Add context to exceptions as they propagate up the stack
```java
try {
    processOrder(order);
} catch (ValidationException e) {
    throw new OrderProcessingException("Order #" + order.getId() + ": " + e.getMessage(), e);
}
```

3. **Selective Catching**: Catch only exceptions you can handle meaningfully
```java
// Bad practice
try {
    // Code
} catch (Exception e) { // Too broad
    // Generic handling that might miss important distinctions
}

// Good practice
try {
    // Code
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    // Specific handling
} catch (IOException e) {
    // More general handling
}
```

Modern exception handling features:

1. **Multi-catch**: Catch multiple exception types in one clause
```java
try {
    // Code
} catch (IOException | SQLException e) {
    // Handle both types the same way
}
```

2. **Try-with-resources**: Automatically close resources that implement `AutoCloseable`
```java
try (InputStream in = new FileInputStream(src);
     OutputStream out = new FileOutputStream(dest)) {
    // Use resources
} // Resources automatically closed
```

3. **Suppressed Exceptions**: When an exception occurs in try and another in try-with-resources close
```java
try (Resource res = new Resource()) {
    throw new FirstException();
} // If res.close() throws SecondException, it's suppressed

// Access suppressed exceptions
catch (FirstException e) {
    Throwable[] suppressed = e.getSuppressed();
    // Process suppressed exceptions
}
```

Defining and using generic classes:
```java
// Generic class definition
public class Box<T> {
    private T content;

    public void put(T content) {
        this.content = content;
    }

    public T get() {
        return content;
    }
}

// Using generics
Box<String> stringBox = new Box<>(); // Diamond operator since Java 7
stringBox.put("Hello");
String content = stringBox.get(); // No casting needed

// Without generics, we'd need casting:
// Box stringBox = new Box();
// stringBox.put("Hello");
// String content = (String) stringBox.get(); // Unsafe cast
```

Methods can also use generics independent of their class:
```java
public class Utilities {
    // Generic method
    public static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list) {
        if (list.isEmpty()) {
            return null;
        }
        return list.get(0);
    }
}

// Usage
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie");
String firstName = Utilities.getFirst(names); // Type inference works here
```

Constraining generic types with bounds:
```java
// Upper bound - T must be Number or a subclass of Number
public class MathBox<T extends Number> {
    private T value;

    public MathBox(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    public double sqrt() {
        return Math.sqrt(value.doubleValue()); // Can use Number methods
    }
}

// Multiple bounds - T must implement Comparable and Serializable
public <T extends Comparable<T> & Serializable> T findMax(List<T> list) {
    // Implementation
}
```

Using wildcards for flexible generic code:
```java
// Unbounded wildcard - accept any type of list
public static void printList(List<?> list) {
    for (Object o : list) {
        System.out.println(o);
    }
}

// Upper bounded wildcard - accept list of Number or its subtypes
public static double sumOfList(List<? extends Number> list) {
    double sum = 0.0;
    for (Number n : list) {
        sum += n.doubleValue();
    }
    return sum;
}

// Lower bounded wildcard - accept list of Integer or its supertypes
public static void addIntegers(List<? super Integer> list) {
    list.add(1);
    list.add(2);
    // list.add("string"); // Compile error
}
```

Producer Extends, Consumer Super (PECS) is a guideline for using bounded wildcards:

- Use **extends** when you only read from a data structure (producer)
- Use **super** when you only write to a data structure (consumer)
- Use no wildcard when you both read and write

```java
// Producer - only reads from source list
public <T> void copy(List<? extends T> source, List<T> destination) {
    for (T item : source) { // Reading from source
        destination.add(item); // Writing to destination
    }
}

// Consumer - only writes to destination list
public <T> void addAll(List<T> source, List<? super T> destination) {
    for (T item : source) {
        destination.add(item); // Writing to destination
    }
}
```

A **reifiable type** is a type whose runtime representation contains all information available at compile time. Due to type erasure, generic types are usually non-reifiable.

- **Reifiable types**: primitives, non-generic types, raw types, unbounded wildcard types
- **Non-reifiable types**: generic types with type arguments

This limitation causes restrictions:
```java
// Not allowed because T[] is non-reifiable
public <T> T[] createArray(int size) {
    return new T[size]; // Compile error
}

// Workaround using Class<T>
public <T> T[] createArray(Class<T> clazz, int size) {
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    T[] array = (T[]) Array.newInstance(clazz, size);
    return array;
}
```

Collections API design patterns with generics:

1. **Recursive Type Parameter** (self-bounding):
```java
public interface Comparable<T> {
    int compareTo(T o);
}

public class Node<T extends Node<T>> {
    // Self-bounding generic
}
```

2. **Static Utility Methods**: Generic static methods in non-generic classes
```java
public class Collections {
    public static <T> void sort(List<T> list, Comparator<? super T> c) {
        // Implementation
    }
}
```

3. **Type Tokens**: Using `Class<T>` to work around type erasure
```java
public class TypeSafeMap {
    private Map<Class<?>, Object> map = new HashMap<>();

    public <T> void put(Class<T> type, T value) {
        map.put(type, value);
    }

    public <T> T get(Class<T> type) {
        return type.cast(map.get(type));
    }
}
```

Design Considerations:
- Prefer generic methods over generic classes when possible
- Use bounded wildcards to increase API flexibility
- Design for generics from the start rather than retrofitting

Consider this generic class:
```java
public class Box<T> {
    private T value;

    public void setValue(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    public T getValue() {
        return value;
    }
}
```

After type erasure, it essentially becomes:
```java
public class Box {
    private Object value;

    public void setValue(Object value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    public Object getValue() {
        return value;
    }
}
```
With appropriate casts inserted at the call sites.

For bounded type parameters, the parameter is replaced with its bound:
```java
public class NumberBox<T extends Number> {
    private T value;

    public T getValue() {
        return value;
    }

    public void setValue(T value) {
        this.value = value;
    }
}
```

After erasure:
```java
public class NumberBox {
    private Number value;

    public Number getValue() {
        return value;
    }

    public void setValue(Number value) {
        this.value = value;
    }
}
```

The compiler generates **bridge methods** to preserve polymorphism in generic code. Consider:
```java
public class StringBox extends Box<String> {
    @Override
    public void setValue(String value) {
        super.setValue(value);
    }
}
```

After erasure, the compiler generates a bridge method in StringBox:
```java
// Bridge method generated by compiler
public void setValue(Object value) {
    setValue((String) value); // Calls the actual method
}
```
This ensures that `StringBox` overrides `Box`'s erased `setValue(Object)` method.

Type erasure imposes several limitations on generic code:

1. **Cannot create instances of generic types**:
```java
public <T> T create() {
    return new T(); // Error: Cannot instantiate type parameter
}
```

2. **Cannot create arrays of generic types**:
```java
public <T> T[] createArray(int size) {
    return new T[size]; // Error: Cannot create generic array
}
```

3. **Cannot use instanceof with generic types**:
```java
if (obj instanceof List<String>) { // Error: Cannot use generic type in instanceof
    // ...
}
// Must use raw type instead
if (obj instanceof List) { // OK but unchecked
    // ...
}
```

4. **Cannot overload methods that would have the same erasure**:
```java
public void process(List<String> strings) { /* ... */ }
public void process(List<Integer> integers) { /* ... */ }
// Error: Both methods have same erasure: process(List)
```

Common workarounds for type erasure limitations:

1. **Using Class objects (type tokens)**:
```java
public <T> T create(Class<T> clazz) throws Exception {
    return clazz.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();
}

public <T> T[] createArray(Class<T> clazz, int size) {
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    T[] array = (T[]) Array.newInstance(clazz, size);
    return array;
}
```

2. **Using super type tokens** (capturing generic type information):
```java
public abstract class TypeReference<T> {
    private final Type type;

    protected TypeReference() {
        Type superclass = getClass().getGenericSuperclass();
        type = ((ParameterizedType) superclass).getActualTypeArguments()[0];
    }

    public Type getType() {
        return type;
    }
}

// Usage
TypeReference<List<String>> typeRef = new TypeReference<List<String>>() {};
Type listStringType = typeRef.getType(); // Captures List<String>
```
This approach is used by libraries like Jackson and Guava.

Guidelines for designing APIs that account for type erasure:

1. **Prefer bounded wildcards** for maximum flexibility:
```java
// Producer: use extends
public void copyFrom(List<? extends E> source) { /* ... */ }

// Consumer: use super
public void addAll(Collection<? super E> destination) { /* ... */ }
```

2. **Consider type tokens for type-safe heterogeneous containers**:
```java
public class TypeSafeMap {
    private Map<Class<?>, Object> map = new HashMap<>();

    public <T> void put(Class<T> type, T value) {
        map.put(type, value);
    }

    public <T> T get(Class<T> type) {
        return type.cast(map.get(type));
    }
}
```

3. **Provide raw type fallbacks when necessary**:
```java
// Method that works with generic type
public <T> void processTyped(List<T> list) { /* ... */ }

// Fallback for when type information is not available
public void process(List<?> list) {
    processTyped(list); // Works due to capture conversion
}
```

4. **Document limitations clearly**:
- Clearly state when methods require runtime type information
- Provide examples for proper API usage
- Warn about potential unchecked casts or type safety concerns

5. **Use runtime checks when necessary**:
```java
public <T> void ensureType(Object obj, Class<T> clazz) {
    if (!clazz.isInstance(obj)) {
        throw new ClassCastException("Object is not of type " + clazz.getName());
    }
}
```

To make a class serializable:
```java
public class Employee implements Serializable {
    // Must have a serialVersionUID for version control
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

    private String name;
    private int id;
    private transient String tempPassword; // Won't be serialized

    // Constructor, getters, setters, etc.
}
```

Basic serialization and deserialization:
```java
// Serializing
Employee emp = new Employee("John Doe", 1001);
try (ObjectOutputStream out = new ObjectOutputStream(
        new FileOutputStream("employee.ser"))) {
    out.writeObject(emp);
}

// Deserializing
try (ObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(
        new FileInputStream("employee.ser"))) {
    Employee emp = (Employee) in.readObject();
}
```

For custom serialization behavior, implement these methods:
```java
private void writeObject(ObjectOutputStream out) throws IOException {
    // Custom serialization logic
    out.defaultWriteObject(); // Write regular fields
    out.writeObject(encryptPassword(password)); // Custom field handling
}

private void readObject(ObjectInputStream in) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
    // Custom deserialization logic
    in.defaultReadObject(); // Read regular fields
    this.password = decryptPassword((String) in.readObject()); // Custom logic
}
```

Serialization recursively processes the entire object graph. All objects referenced by the serialized object must also implement `Serializable`. Non-serializable objects in the graph must be:
- Marked `transient`
- Reconstructed during deserialization

Example handling non-serializable fields:
```java
public class Report implements Serializable {
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
    private String name;
    private transient Connection dbConnection; // Cannot be serialized

    private void readObject(ObjectInputStream in) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
        in.defaultReadObject();
        // Reconnect to the database after deserialization
        this.dbConnection = DatabaseManager.getConnection();
    }
}
```

Beyond basic methods, Java offers more control mechanisms:

1. **Externalizable interface**: Complete control over serialization process
```java
public class ExternalizableEmployee implements Externalizable {
    private String name;
    private int id;

    // No-arg constructor REQUIRED for Externalizable
    public ExternalizableEmployee() {}

    @Override
    public void writeExternal(ObjectOutput out) throws IOException {
        // Complete control over what gets written
        out.writeUTF(name);
        out.writeInt(id);
    }

    @Override
    public void readExternal(ObjectInput in) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
        // Must read in same order as written
        name = in.readUTF();
        id = in.readInt();
    }
}
```

2. **Serialization proxies pattern**: Safer alternative to direct serialization
```java
public class Period implements Serializable {
    private final Date start;
    private final Date end;

    // Private constructor for safe creation
    private Period(Date start, Date end) {
        this.start = new Date(start.getTime()); // Defensive copy
        this.end = new Date(end.getTime());     // Defensive copy
        if (this.start.compareTo(this.end) > 0)
            throw new IllegalArgumentException();
    }

    // Serialization proxy
    private static class SerializationProxy implements Serializable {
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
        private final Date start;
        private final Date end;

        SerializationProxy(Period p) {
            this.start = p.start;
            this.end = p.end;
        }

        // Automatically invoked during deserialization
        private Object readResolve() {
            return new Period(start, end); // Uses validation constructor
        }
    }

    // This method is invoked by serialization system
    private Object writeReplace() {
        return new SerializationProxy(this);
    }

    // Prevent attacker from creating invalid instance
    private void readObject(ObjectInputStream in) throws InvalidObjectException {
        throw new InvalidObjectException("Proxy required");
    }
}
```
